Wash and dry produce. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Thinly slice @chili pepper{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add half the ginger and cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup}, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Place broccoli in a large #microwave-safe bowl{}; cover tightly with #plastic wrap{} and poke a few holes in wrap. Microwave until broccoli is tender, ~{1-2%minutes}. Carefully uncover (watch out for steam!) and toss broccoli with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: No microwave? No problem! Bring a medium pot of salted water to a boil. Add broccoli; cook until tender, 2-4 minutes. Drain; season with salt and pepper.

Meanwhile, pat @skin-on salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #medium pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon and cook, skin sides down, until skin is crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}, then flip and cook until cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{}. Wipe out pan.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @apricot jam{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1} and @water{2%tbsp}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for salmon over medium heat. Add remaining ginger and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in jam mixture and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. If sauce seems too thick, stir in water a splash at a time.

Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Season with salt and pepper.

Thinly slice salmon crosswise.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1/2%tbsp} and season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice and broccoli between plates. Top rice with salmon and drizzle with sauce. Garnish with chili to taste and serve.

> Use pan used for chicken or salmon here. Thinly slice chicken crosswise (skip slicing salmon!). > Swap in chicken for pork. Cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side.